f wealth is money. Assets and belongings aren't always considered part of wealth, but rather as the result of wealth.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Not to sidetrack into an exestentalist and Marxists viewpoints here, but...just throwing out food for thought.<br>
<br>
A.  Assets ARE monitary weath IF they can be tranfered into money.  Hence, sell a home, get a few million dollars (money, itself...just transfered into a different form, still the same on your financial statement in either form..thus STILL overall 'monitary' WEALTH).<br>
<br>
<br>
B.  If someone is well educated and intelligent, they COULD very well be BROKE their whole life...but NEVER poor.  Education is a form of wealth (due to INCREASED quality of life...another FORM of wealth).  Some people use it and some do not. <br>
<br>
Or if you want to talk about economics itself per authoritarian socialism,  as in the U.S.S.R., The Union of Soviet SOCIALIST (NOT communist) Republic.  Karl Marx theorizes on (autoritarian socialisim AS pre-communism tranferance) that in economy, QUANTITY (of goods OR actions) EFFECT quality.  Thus, the more, the RICHER (monitarily OR lifestyle wise).  Or the OVER production...causing lack of demand and low economic states.<br>
<br>
As for DEMOCRATIC Socialism...well, I don't have much to add that has not already been discussed.  Plus I have a patient in 5 minutes, LOL!  <br>
<br>
But I will say this, when I was younger I though it was a GREAT theory.  Now that I have seen it in practice, I think that QUALITY (of life, healthcare, education) go DOWN for eveyone under a democratic socialist system.<br>
<br>
  My husband who is English disagrees.  He like the idea of EVERYONE getting medical care, become better educated when they want/need it (like he had in England).  I think that (in the US at least) we STILL have that.  Medicare pays for people with health problems who can NOT afford.  State University systems give GRANTS (no LOANS) for people to attend collage if they can not afford it, etc.  So I see no NEED to tax us all to over 50% when we already ARE taking care of people that need to be helped.  JMO<br>
<br>
But ya know...a lot DOES come down into what you are born into.  Education (among other things...primarly travel and age) can manipulate it.  Either way though...that's life.  Some people have a CHOICE to create their own paths and some people DO NOT (in places where they are TOLD what to do and ONLY what to do and are not educated enough to know the get the hell outa there and strive for more). <p><center><img src="http://www.boomspeed.com/apothokeri/DraccaSig.gif"><br><br><b><font face="garamond" size=3><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=543802">My Magelo Profile</a></center><font size=0 font face=garamond font color=black></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=draccaviir>Dracca Viir</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.boomspeed.com/apothokeri/staricon.jpg" BORDER=0> at: 1/22/03 9:08:04 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caenn>Caenn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#333333>(1/23/03 9:44:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=72>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: idiot socialists</span><hr size=1> Wow!  This is an awesome thread.  Too bad I happened across it so late <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->       .  I'm not going to pick apart every comment in every post.  I'd be here all night.  Just going to add my two cents on a few comments that caught my eye.  I'm sure this will nonetheless turn into a very long post.  Sorry <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->       .<br>
<br>
I'd like to make two points right up front:<br>
     <br>
     1) Others have touched on the point that pure capitalism is not necessarily feasible and must be regulated by some form of socialism.  I most definately agree with this concept, though the degree to which it must be regulated is a matter for debate.  Just know that when I refer to &quot;capitalism&quot;, I am referring to it in this context.<br>
     <br>
     2) While it may be &quot;cliche&quot; and smack of &quot;rhetorical, brainwashed drivel&quot; (as will other parts of this post) and serve as fodder for some of the over-educated pseudo-intelligent types out there, like it or not, a society centered around the free market economy has made the United States of America (arguably) the most powerful nation that has ever existed at any time in history.  And it's happened in a relative flash-in-the-pan of 200 or so years.<br>
    <br>
Well, here we go...<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Silverblade: &quot;One rich person BUYS the rights to that heart or can afford the operation and you can't.<br>
is that fair?&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, that is most definately not how it happens...at least in the United States.  This is quite simply a broad and false assumption/generalization on your part, which, I think, is indicitave of most of your stated positions.  I think you probably know this, but you're so fond of demonizing the capitalistic system that you've indulged yourself to such melodramatic rantings throughout much of your input to this thread.<br>
<br>
For what it's worth, transplantation recipients are placed on priority lists and given organs according to how compatible they may be with a given donor organ.  The wealth of the recipient is completely irrelevant.  There is a rather (in)famous case still getting some attention here in the US where a two-time violent felon received a heart transplant <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>while incarcerated</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Cost to the state of California (i.e. ME) was supposedly in excess of $1 million.  <br>
<br>
You see, even in our hateful, cold, fiendishly capitalist society, there is a safety net which provides life-saving health care for those who cannot afford any other health care.  Granted it doesn't include in-home doctor visits, but, well, so what?  If people want that, they can go out and get a job that allows them to afford it.  And don't say that it cannot be done, because I am living proof that indeed it can.  I am sick to my stomach of listening to apologists for the lazy and advocates for the unambitious tell me what can and cannot be done.  I come from nothing and have made something of my life.  Enough said.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Melik001: &quot;I have yet to see ANY form of government work the way it was intended. Human greed will always taint even the noblest intentions.&quot;<br>
<br>
Other posters to this thread have stated much more eloquently than I could why you are correct.  I'd just like to expound a bit by saying that the true genious of the capitalistic system lies in the fact that it doesn't just accomodate this human trait, it wholly embraces it.  Humans will act the way that humans will act and no law or governing system will ever change that...and THAT is why systems based on universal equality not only will not work, but <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>cannot</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> work.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Silverblade: &quot;People should have the right to CHOSE their doctor, but *nobody* should *EVER* be able to *BUY* better health care than someone else, except when it's purely cosmetic surgery (which is usally a want, not a need).&quot;<br>
<br>
This is just plain asinine.  Unlike you, evidently, I believe that I was born into this world owed nothing.  I have the maturity and the character to understand that *GASP* there <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>will be</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> people in the world who can afford bigger and better things than I can.  If they've been able to figure out how to do that, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>more power to them!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  They have just as much right to better health care as they do to a bigger TV and a faster car.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Everyone go back and read Sarabeth's post on page one.  Careful now, you might learn something.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Belarkan: &quot;In light of events in middle east (preparation for war on Irak, a country not related to Bin Laden, but a huge oil producer....)&quot;<br>
<br>
First of all, I'm making the assumption based on your posts that you do not live in the United States.  Please forgive me if I am wrong.  But my sentiment is still the same.<br>
<br>
We are a country that lost over 2,800 people in one fell swoop to middle eastern Islamic terrorists - something that the rest of the world seems to have already forgotten.  Perhaps where you come from that could be dismissed and written off, but not here.  I am sick and goddamned tired of people who cannot <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>possibly</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> understand the dynamic of what is going on in my country right now trivializing our actions by attempting to boil it down to oil.  <br>
<br>
/rhetorical, brainwashed drivel on <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->       ...<br>
I, for one, happen to understand how precious our way of life is, and I am grateful beyond words that we have leaders with the testicular fortitude to do what needs to be done to protect it.  I won't even get into the reasons for us doing what we're doing in Iraq, or what ties there may or may not be with Al Qaeda.  But suffice it to say that, as is usually the case, YOU will sleep safer tonight thanks to OUR blood and sweat.  Whether or not you can swallow your pride long enough to admit this to yourself is another issue.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
